<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8868&amp;p=93608#p93608</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8868&amp;p=93608#p93608"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[2a0x APU &quot;TEST&quot; features.]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8868&amp;p=93608#p93608"><![CDATA[
The noise channel probably emits nonzero when the LFSR output is in one state and zero when the output is in the other state. Only one bit at a time is available, and it isn't very random because it depends solely on the time since the channel was reset divided by the period divider. This in turn depends on the number of CPU cycles, which is predictable. It'd be easier just to use a subroutine to simulate clocking a 16-bit LFSR eight times, like <a href="http://www.6502.org/source/integers/crc-more.html" class="postlink">Greg Cook's CRC16</a>.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Thu May 10, 2012 4:40 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
